article.headline: Wisconsin 68, Valparaiso 58
article.story: MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Wisconsin overcame a sloppy performance and poor free-throw shooting Saturday night to beat Valparaiso 68-58. Wisconsin (9-2) came into the game outscoring its nonranked opponents by almost 30 points a game. But Valparaiso (10-2) led much of the second half despite foul trouble for its post players, thanks largely to Wisconsin's ball-handling problems and free-throw woes. The Badgers committed 20 turnovers and shot just 17-of-36 (47 percent) from the free-throw line. They came into the game hitting almost 70 percent of their foul shots. Wisconsin trailed by as many as seven early in the second half, but steadily clawed back. Trevon Hughes gave Wisconsin its first lead of the game with just over two minutes left, shaking his defender to hit a 3-pointer from the top of the key to make it 57-54. That was the beginning of a 14-4 run to finish the game as the Crusaders fell apart down the stretch. Hughes led Wisconsin with 14 points, while Joe Krabbenhoft added 11 points and 11 rebounds. Jason Bohannon scored 10 points. Three Crusaders fouled out of the game, and two of their post players were forced to miss large stretches of the second half with foul trouble. Starting forward Urule Igbavboa went to the bench less than three minutes into the second half with his fourth foul. He was followed three minutes later by reserve forward Bryan Bouchie, who was also forced to sit with his fourth foul. Both later fouled out. The Crusaders were whistled for eight fouls in the first 5:30 of the second half, putting the Badgers in the bonus. Wisconsin was in the double bonus for the final 10 minutes of the game. But they couldn't take advantage of it. Samuel Haanpaa led Valparaiso with 16 points, while Brandon McPherson added 14. Valparaiso was off to its best start in school history coming into Saturday night's game, the first of two tough road contests for the Crusaders. They travel to No. 1 North Carolina Dec. 30.
